The set \( A \) consists of all numbers of the form \( n + x \), where \( n \in \mathbb{Z} \) and \( x \) is a number in the Cantor set (since the sum over \( p \) with \( a_p = 0 \) or 1 gives numbers in \([0,1]\) with binary expansion using only even negative powers, which is a Cantor-type set of measure zero).  
Thus \( A \) is a countable union of translates of a null set, so its Lebesgue measure is zero.  

